<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 25 日星期二 08:00:06 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine’s Stalled Offensive Puts Biden in Uneasy Political Position]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>由于实际进展缓慢，政府对基辅与莫斯科谈判的希望逐渐破灭<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822600/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="乌克兰士兵向乌克兰东部扎波罗热地区的俄罗斯阵地开火。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乌克兰士兵向乌克兰东部扎波罗热地区的俄罗斯阵地开火。 Dmytro Smoliyenko/UKRINFORM/Zuma Press <span>Dmytro Smoliyenko/UKRINFORM/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">戈登·卢伯德 (Gordon Lubold)</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·R·戈登 (Michael R. Gordon)</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/warren-p-strobel" itemprop="url" rel="author">沃伦·P·史特罗贝尔 (Warren P. Strobel)</a></span>和</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>西方官员表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-seeks-to-divert-ukrainian-forces-away-from-counteroffensive-80580e89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，乌克兰对根深蒂固的俄罗斯侵略者的反攻步伐</a>缓慢，使得今年结束战斗的谈判的希望变得渺茫，并引发了无休止冲突的担忧。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜在的僵局</a>将考验拜登总统向乌克兰提供数十亿美元军事援助的既定战略，以使基辅能够以强势地位与俄罗斯进行谈判。它还可能挑战西方持续供应本已短缺的武器的能力，并为那些反对美国支持战争的人提供政治素材。</p><p> “显然，当事情进展顺利时，提供更多支持会更容易，”前美国驻乌克兰大使、扩大对基辅军事援助的倡导者约翰·赫布斯特说。但他说，拜登政府除了继续提供武器外别无选择。</p><p>赫布斯特补充说，从乌克兰撤军，甚至允许俄罗斯取得部分胜利，“将是拜登外交政策的标志性失败，这将使阿富汗撤军相形见绌”。赫布斯特目前供职于华盛顿大西洋理事会智囊团。</p><p>然而，美国的“坚持到底”战略也存在一些风险。拜登把他的外交政策信誉押在了一场他称之为民主与威权主义之间的斗争的冲突上。他已向基辅提供了超过 430 亿美元的安全援助，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mccarthy-opposes-extra-ukraine-spending-after-debt-deal-cf967c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在国会面临来自一些共和党成员的挑战</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822598?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">拜登总统已向乌克兰提供超过 430 亿美元的安全援助。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亨里克·蒙哥马利/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周四，13 名参议院共和党人支持年度国防支出法案的一项修正案，该法案将限制乌克兰的可用资金。该修正案失败了，国会其他共和党人对乌克兰的支持依然强劲。</p><p>随着拜登明年参加总统竞选，俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>更有动力试图超越西方。共和党提名的两位主要竞争者——前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>和佛罗里达州州长<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>——表示他们可能会减弱对乌克兰的军事支持。</p><p>俄罗斯也没有表现出任何谈判的意愿。随着对乌克兰的入侵陷入困境， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">普京面临着国内的批评者</a>，他们说他没有足够积极地进行战争。</p><p> “俄罗斯人非常乐意谈论乌克兰的投降，”外交关系委员会杰出研究员托马斯·格雷厄姆说。 “我认为他们对目前尚未解决乌克兰危机的任何谈判都不太感兴趣。”</p><p>乌克兰于6月初发起反攻，旨在夺回被莫斯科占领的近20%的乌克兰领土中的部分领土。虽然乌克兰夺回了部分领土，但尚未取得可能迫使俄罗斯坐到谈判桌前的突破。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C97C88D4-572D-4836-8A1A-666E07F3B3AE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">俄罗斯指责乌克兰周一早些时候对莫斯科发动无人机袭击。俄罗斯国防部表示，无人机被拦截，莫斯科市长表示，没有收到严重损坏或受伤的报告。照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>拜登在本月早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-visit-cements-finlands-pivot-away-from-neutrality-3fd65237?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">访问赫尔辛基</a>时表示：“我的希望和预期是，你们会看到乌克兰在攻势上取得重大进展，并在某个地方通过谈判达成解决方案。”</p><p>由于俄罗斯和乌克兰都不愿意谈判，白宫目前别无选择，只能坚持到底，希望最终能在战场上取得突破，对抗根深蒂固的俄罗斯军队，或者莫斯科出现新的政治裂痕。</p><p>美国官员承认反攻进展缓慢，但表示，在乌克兰派遣更多战斗旅之前评估反攻效果还为时过早，尤其是那些在美国欧洲基地接受过装甲机动战训练的旅。</p><p>一位美国官员表示：“如果他们承诺储备，但储备不成功，那么我们将不得不确定未来的方向。”</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周日在接受 CNN 采访时表示，攻势仍处于初期阶段，自 2022 年 2 月俄罗斯发动全面入侵以来，乌克兰“已收回了最初缴获的约 50%”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822597?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰敖德萨，工人在罢工后清理瓦砾。俄罗斯几乎没有表现出谈判的意愿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：oleksandr gimanov/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="902" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822596?width=1260&amp;height=902" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰东部的乌克兰士兵。美国官员承认反攻进展缓慢。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Oleksandr Ratushniak/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一位欧洲高级官员表示，基辅的任务是一项艰巨的任务，他表示，他的政府几乎不指望乌克兰军队能够将俄罗斯军队驱逐出整个乌克兰东部或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">夺回克里米亚</a>。他承认，虽然惊喜是有可能的，但可能性并不一定。</p><p>这位官员表示：“我们并不指望他们能够收复俄罗斯失去的所有领土，尤其是考虑到克里米亚，甚至是 2014 年顿巴斯失去的领土。”该官员是乌克兰的坚定支持者之一。</p><p>美国及其盟国面临的另一个挑战是关键武器储备的减少，华盛顿最近试图通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向基辅提供集束弹药来部分解决这一短缺问题。</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国应该向乌克兰提供多少支持？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>英国外交大臣上周在阿斯彭安全论坛上向记者发表讲话</p>詹姆斯·克莱弗利表示，美国和西方国家必须继续尽可能多地、尽快地向乌克兰供应物资。<p></p><p> “人们说，‘是的，但你知道吗，我们不能让橱柜空着。你必须把它保存起来以备不时之需，”他说。 “我的意思是，今天是下雨天。”</p><p>华盛顿的一位西方外交官表示，美国可能不得不接受乌克兰战争不会很快结束的事实，盟友需要做好为基辅提供物资的准备，以应对持续数年的冲突。</p><p>这位外交官表示：“唯一真正的回应是工业动员，这将向乌克兰人和俄罗斯人传达一个明确的信息：乌克兰人将永远拥有充足的需求。”</p><p>问题是，如果攻势继续低于预期，美国及其盟友是否有决心继续支持，甚至扩大支持。乌克兰的首要愿望是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-close-to-approving-long-range-atacms-missiles-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-cc4e389c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国制造的 ATACMS</a>远程导弹和更快地采购 F-16 战斗机。</p><p>加拿大副总理克里斯蒂亚·弗里兰上周在阿斯本安全论坛上发表讲话，公开担心西方盟友坚持到底的能力。</p><p> “实际上，我对乌克兰最大的恐惧是我们，”她说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Alan Cullison、William Mauldin 和 Sharon Weinberger 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Gordon Lubold ( <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com)</a> 、Michael R. Gordon ( <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Warren P. Strobel ( <a href="mailto:Warren.Strobel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Warren.Strobel@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offective-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offective-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5<author><![CDATA[Gordon LuboldMichael R. GordonWarren P. Strobel]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>拜登总统</category><category>约翰·赫布斯特</category><category>托马斯·格雷厄姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel Approves Part of Netanyahu’s Controversial Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在立法者未能达成妥协后，总理联盟投票支持立法<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079176"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E3E72531-794A-477C-836E-5960EF41E94A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联盟周一通过了一项有争议的司法改革中的第一项法案，旨在限制最高法院的权力。 《华尔街日报》的多夫·利伯从耶路撒冷报道。照片：Corinna Kern/路透社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079176"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯 (Dov Lieber)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shayndi-raice" itemprop="url" rel="author">Shayndi Raice</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 6:19（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>耶路撒冷——以色列议会无视<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-flare-up-in-new-push-to-stop-judicial-overhaul-9f939aac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数月的抗议</a>，通过了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-netanyahu-pushes-ahead-with-vote-on-judicial-overhaul-as-protests-intensify-d29b1b55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一项引起分歧的司法改革</a>，使该国进一步陷入政治危机，暴露了其身份上的分歧，并引发了对其国家安全的担忧。</p><p>总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联盟周一在没有任何反对派支持的情况下通过了这项法律，这标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，可能会与该国最高法院摊牌，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">该法律旨在遏制该</a>机构的权力。对于数千名表示将退出的预备役军人以及威胁要大规模停工的企业、工会领导人和医疗专业人员来说，这是一个决定性的时刻。</p><p>这可能会使以色列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-netanyahu-agree-to-meet-later-this-year-247c33f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和其他盟国的关系</a>复杂化，这些盟国长期以来一直认为以色列是中东唯一成熟的民主国家。拜登总统采取了不同寻常的步骤，呼吁内塔尼亚胡在通过立法之前做出妥协。白宫发表声明称该法案的通过“不幸”。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡领导的由 64 名议员组成的整个联盟对该法案投了赞成票，他们被广泛视为该国 75 年历史上最右翼、民族主义和宗教色彩最浓厚的人。他们对这项法律表示欢迎，该法律剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力——他们认为这一概念含糊不清，并允许自由派法官推翻日益右翼选民的意愿。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822518?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列立法者周一在批准总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的部分司法改革后举行庆祝活动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这是联盟希望通过的一系列限制法院系统权力的法律中的第一部。接下来是一项法案，该法案将赋予立法者更多选择法官的权力，这一举措比周一通过的法案更具争议性。它可能会在秋季进行投票。</p><p> “我们在修复司法系统的历史性进程中迈出了第一步，”司法部长亚里夫·莱文(Yariv Levin)说，他被广泛认为是此次改革的设计者。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡在周一晚上的一次讲话中表示，他的联盟将继续与反对派接触，以便就未来的任何司法立法达成协议。</p><p> “没有一方会控制法庭。这不可能发生。在我们的领导下，这不会发生，”内塔尼亚胡说。</p><p>该法案在达成妥协的谈判破裂后获得通过。反对派议员走出房间，抵制投票。</p><p>周一全国爆发大规模示威活动，并计划在深夜举行更多示威活动。警方努力阻止抗议者冲击议会。数万人高呼“民主！”当他们挤满以色列议会和其他政府大楼附近的耶路撒冷街道时，他们吹响了响亮的号角。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          inline
"></div><p> “我们拒绝接受这一点，”34 岁的罗伊·巴沙 (Roee Basha) 说。“我们都很清楚，别无选择。我们要么升级，要么离开这个国家。”</p><p>根据以色列第 12 频道播放的视频，警方称，数十名抗议者被捕，当局强行驱散了特拉维夫封锁街道的一些示威者。视频显示，警方在特拉维夫使用高压水枪驱散抗议者。</p><p></p>反对派领袖亚伊尔·拉皮德称该法案的通过是“以色列民主的破坏”。<p></p><p> “我们不会放弃，”他说。 “我们不会投降。我们不会让他们把以色列变成一个破碎的、不民主的、由仇恨和极端主义统治的国家。”</p><p>周一的立法行动可能引发一系列非同寻常的事件，这些事件将考验以色列的团结，包括在最高法院面前对法律提出挑战。一个非政府组织表示，它周一向法院提出请愿，声称该法律从根本上改变了以色列民主的性质，并且通过该法律的程序存在缺陷。</p><p>耶路撒冷希伯来大学法学教授尤瓦尔·沙尼表示：“我们距离宪法摊牌又近了一步。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822439?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，以色列警方在耶路撒冷以色列议会外示威期间阻止了抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kobi Wolf/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周一的立法是对以色列所谓基本法之一的修正案，这是该国最接近宪法的零碎立法。沙尼表示，法官们从未推翻过一项基本法，但在各种裁决中表示，如果它从根本上改变了以色列民主的性质，或者滥用了宪法程序，法院有权这样做。</p><p>该法案的通过对以色列军队构成了挑战，以色列军队通常因依赖志愿者储备而被称为“人民军队”。司法改革疏远了许多预备役军人，他们中的一些人认为此举是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">极端正统犹太人夺取权力的行为</a>，而他们中的绝大多数人并不在军队服役。</p><p>数千名预备役军人本周表示，如果该法案获得通过，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-faces-fresh-stand-off-with-israeli-reservists-over-judicial-overhaul-b974d3f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将停止报到志愿服务</a>，不过他们是否会兑现这一承诺还有待观察。军方官员警告说，这项立法正在破坏军队内部的团结。</p><p> “我无话可说。我想哭，”来自内坦亚的预备役战斗士兵和心理学学生本·利维 (Ben Levy) 在周一投票后说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822441?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列警察试图驱散堵塞通往耶路撒冷议会道路的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他说，很可能会有更多的预备役军人宣布他们将不再服役，而且许多人会找借口不出现，悄悄地这样做。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡是该国任职时间最长的总理，现已进入第六个任期，在他的政府于三月份首次试图通过另一套不同的法案后，他使司法立法从失败中恢复过来。在大规模抗议和大罢工导致国家瘫痪后，他推迟了这项努力，但他上个月表示，他将以修改后的形式通过这项改革。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡在安装起搏器后于周一出院，他历来都不是改革司法机构的倡导者，但他面临着从右翼通过这一法案的巨大压力，这使他在议会中获得微弱多数。</p><p>另一边是拜登、商界领袖和数十万抗议者，他们每个周末都进行示威，持续了六个多月。周一，该国主要工会以色列总工会表示，正在为可能举行的总罢工做准备，这可能会再次削弱该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822442?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">鸟瞰图显示耶路撒冷议会附近搭建的帐篷，抗议政府的司法改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ILAN ROSENBERG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>关于司法立法的辩论揭示了以色列社会对于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">犹太国家和民主国家的</a>意义的分歧。该国在成立之初的几十年里是由主要是东欧血统的世俗社会主义者建立和控制的。他们设想了一个文化上犹太教但社会上自由民主的国家。近几十年来，代表以色列右翼的不同阶层——宗教犹太复国主义者、定居者、极端正统派和中东裔犹太人——之间的联盟在数量和力量上都在增长。内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团本身是世俗的，它已将这些右翼势力联合成一个政治强国。</p><p> “这是以色列人和犹太人之间的冲突，”耶路撒冷希伯来大学政治学系主任吉迪恩·拉哈特说。他说，以色列人代表了设想世俗犹太复国主义国家的创始人，而犹太人则是那些想要重建 2000 年前统治这片土地的犹太王国的人。</p><p> “这是更公民的身份和更宗教的身份之间的冲突，”他说。</p><p>在一个没有强大总统职位的国家，最高法院长期以来一直是政府执政联盟的唯一制衡机构，近年来经常阻挠右翼政府的决定。最近的一个例子是，法院取消了内塔尼亚胡对一位重要的极端正统盟友的任命，该盟友被判犯有腐败和逃税罪，担任内政、卫生部长和财政部长。</p><p>以色列财政部长贝扎莱尔·斯莫特里奇表示，联盟正试图“恢复政府各部门之间的平衡”。</p><p> “我们将共同继续负责任地进行修复，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822521?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在耶路撒冷议会附近的示威活动中，抗议者被警察高压水枪喷射。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：RONEN ZVULUN/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>来自以色列北部城市海法的 27 岁社会工作者霍达亚·加农 (Hodaya Ganon) 表示，周一通过这项立法被视为对右翼选民期待已久的认可。她说：“到目前为止，所有以前的右翼政府都以牺牲选民为代价屈从于对方的意愿，尽管他们以公平和民主的方式获胜。”</p><p>部分原因是内塔尼亚胡的法律问题导致该国走到这一步。内塔尼亚胡执政二十年的大部分时间里，建立了右翼、中间派和左翼联盟。 2019 年，他被指控贿赂和欺诈（他对此予以否认），之后他的前中间派伙伴，甚至一些右翼人士，拒绝与他一起参与政府工作，导致他短暂失去权力。当他去年年底重新担任总理时，他建立了一个联盟，其中包括两个极端正统政党和一个极端民族主义者联盟。</p><p>总部位于耶路撒冷的以色列民主研究所的法律和犹太研究学者什洛米特·拉维茨基·图尔-帕斯表示，尽管右翼已经掌权数十年，但许多选民感觉这个国家似乎是由世俗的自由派精英统治的，这一点在法院所掌握的权力中表现得最为明显。</p><p> “他们仍然觉得自己没有权力，”她说。 “所以这就是他们现在正在努力改变的。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（dov.lieber@wsj.com）</a>和 Shayndi Raice（ <a href="mailto:Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3<author><![CDATA[Dov LieberShayndi Raice]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[North Korea Hasn’t Answered U.S.’s Calls on Detained Soldier]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国国务院称，美国士兵越过边境后不久就没有“新的通讯” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079129"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D218996D-CA76-4EBA-85A1-7ED736A7A86E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国国务院发言人表示，美国尚未收到朝鲜关于被拘留在朝鲜的美国士兵特拉维斯·金下落的回应。照片：Ahn Young-Joon/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079129"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span> （首尔）和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gordon Lubold</a></span> （华盛顿）</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 5:49（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国官员表示，美国已就<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一名上周从韩国越过边境的美国士兵</a>问题与朝鲜进行了接触，但迄今为止平壤尚未做出回应。</p><p>英国陆军中将安德鲁·哈里森 (Andrew Harrison) 在周一的简报中表示，美国试图利用根据 1950-53 年朝鲜战争结束的停战协议建立的通讯线路与朝鲜进行对话。美国官员表示，美国至少通过两个渠道进行接触，但平壤尚未参与。</p><p>一名美国官员表示：“我们已通过多种渠道向[朝鲜]传达了该人自行越境的信息，我们希望他迅速安全地返回。” “我们还要求提供有关他福利的更多信息。”这位官员表示，美国知道朝鲜已收到该信息，但不会进一步详细说明。</p><p>驻首尔的联合国司令部由一名美国将军领导，他也领导着驻韩美军，该司令部已尝试与平壤接触。官员们表示，白宫利用瑞典作为中间人，也做出了类似的尝试。</p><p>美国国务院发言人还表示，自金首次飞行以来，联合国和朝鲜一直没有保持定期联系。发言人马特·米勒否认了有关联合国司令部与朝鲜保持定期接触的报道，并暗示存在“误解”。</p><p>马特·米勒说：“除了他越过边境后的凌晨或几天内发生的通讯之外，我不知道有任何新的通讯。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="480" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822426?width=700&amp;height=480" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">联合国军司令部副司令、英国陆军中将安德鲁·哈里森在周一的新闻发布会上发表了讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：jung yeon-je/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> 23 岁的二等兵特拉维斯·金 (Travis King) 上周二参观联合安全区时越过边境，随后被朝鲜拘留。联合安全区是分隔朝韩两国的非军事区的一部分。</p><p> “我们最关心的是二等兵国王的福利，”哈里森说。他表示他仍然乐观，但拒绝提供会谈的细节，理由是会谈的敏感性。</p><p>官员上周表示，在金跨越边境的前一天，他已准备飞往德克萨斯州接受纪律处分，并可能因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去年发生两起袭击事件</a>而被解雇。他已在韩国的一所拘留所被关押了 47 天。</p><p>朝鲜没有公开谈论过金的情况。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">国王十字路口事件</a>引发了人们对美军海外基地人员处理方式的质疑。上周一，美国军人护送他前往仁川机场，并在金通过安全检查站后离开。金告诉航空公司工作人员，他找不到自己的护照，然后溜出了机场。第二天，他随旅游团前往联合安全区。</p><p>负责管理驻韩美军 28,500 名人员的驻韩美军发言人表示，该事件仍在调查中。</p><p>金据称去年 9 月袭击了一名韩国公民，下个月又参与了另一次袭击，并踢坏了一辆警车，并因此被罚款 4,000 美元。陆军部长</p>克里斯汀·沃穆斯 (Christine Wormuth) 在上周四的新闻发布会上推测，金一直在努力应对返回美国后将面临的后果。<p></p><p>朝鲜观察人士表示，金自愿进入朝鲜可能会使他的获释变得困难。过去，朝鲜曾利用美国士兵的叛逃作为宣传机会，将美国人描绘成对资本主义日益失望的人。陆军中士。查尔斯·詹金斯 (Charles Jenkins) 于 1965 年辞去在韩国的职务并逃往朝鲜，成为朝鲜电影中的常见人物，在剧中饰演资本主义恶棍。</p><p>自<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/even-before-trump-and-kim-met-nuclear-talks-had-run-aground-11551487094?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2019年河内核谈判破裂</a>以来，朝鲜一直拒绝与美国进行对话。最近几周，朝鲜高级官员发表声明，猛烈抨击华盛顿向韩国部署核潜艇<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">肯塔基号</a>等战略资产。上周四，朝鲜国防部长警告称，该潜艇的存在可能成为平壤使用核武器的理由。</p><p>周一，美国核动力潜艇安纳波利斯号抵达韩国济州岛的一个港口，作为针对朝鲜日益增长的核和导弹威胁的又一武力展示。韩国海军发言人表示，美国和韩国正在讨论是否让这艘潜艇参与训练。</p><p>金氏政权在 7 月 27 日这个被称为胜利日的重大节日之前加强了导弹试验。韩国军方称，当地时间周一晚上 11 点 55 分，朝鲜在东海岸发射了两枚短程弹道导弹。平壤主要官方报纸《劳动新闻》周一发表社论，声称加强军事建设对于维护和平是必要的。</p><p> 《劳动新闻》表示，“加强军事力量是没有止境的”。</p><p>写信给 Dasl Yoon（ <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com）</a>和 Gordon Lubold（ <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonGordon Lubold]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>安德鲁·哈里森</category><category>特拉维斯·金</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Fed Isn’t Ready to Declare Victory on Inflation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>官员们仍然担心在经济不衰退的情况下工资和物价增长是否会足够放缓<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074296"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822097?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美联储上个月维持基准联邦基金利率稳定，但预计本周将加息。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：内森霍华德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074296"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nick-timiraos" itemprop="url" rel="author">尼克·蒂米罗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 24 日下午 5:16（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-fed-isnt-ready-to-declare-victory-on-inflation-e882b4d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>今年夏天晚些时候通胀路径的不确定性使得人们很难预测美联储在本周可能加息四分之一个百分点后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-fed-debate-this-month-what-would-prompt-a-rate-hike-this-fall-a7e9f83e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的下一步行动</a>。</p><p>一些美联储政策制定者和经济学家担心<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/last-mile-of-the-inflation-fight-will-be-the-hardest-86bcebb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀的缓解</a>将是暂时的。他们认为，在推高租金以及交通和汽车价格的流行病相关冲击消退之后，通胀放缓早就应该出现了。他们担心潜在的价格压力可能持续存在，从而要求美联储提高利率并维持更长的时间。</p><p>其他经济学家表示，这种想法忽视了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-market-headfake-key-report-could-be-overestimating-job-growth-c7ea020?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">当前经济放缓</a>的迹象，而这种迹象将逐渐缓解价格压力。他们还认为，未来几个月通胀将放缓，足以推高“实际”利率或通胀调整后的利率。即使本周的加息是当前紧缩周期的最后一次，这也将提供额外的货币限制。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F0A8BD11-B153-4E7E-8454-B5C1C8CD12BD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhy-the-fed-isnt-ready-to-declare-victory-on-inflation-e882b4d9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">通胀正在缓慢缓解，但距离美联储2%的目标仍相去甚远。 《华尔街日报》的 Nick Timiraos 解释了 2% 如何成为央行的最佳点，以及当美国经济偏离该点太远时会发生什么。照片插图：Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>美联储上个月将基准联邦基金利率稳定在5%至5.25%的范围内，这是自2022年3月官员将利率从接近于零的水平上调以来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/a-world-transformed-by-5-percentage-points-5289d835?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">连续10次加息</a>后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-holds-rates-steady-but-expects-more-increases-b1be87f2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的首次暂停</a>。</p><p>加息会降低资产价格并提高借贷成本，从而通过金融市场减缓经济发展。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">上个月通胀降至</a>两年来最低水平。 6 月份消费者价格指数同比上涨 3%，远低于 2022 年 6 月 9.1% 的近期峰值。排除波动较大的食品和能源价格的核心通胀指数 6 月份也录得两年多以来的最小月度涨幅。</p><p>哈佛大学经济学家凯伦·戴南 (Karen Dynan) 表示：“虽然通货膨胀似乎正朝着正确的方向发展，但我们才刚刚处于一个漫长过程的开始。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          inline
"></div><h3>追赶通胀调整后的薪资增长</h3><p>第一阵营的经济学家感到紧张，因为经济中的松弛太少而需求太多，以至于无法合理地相信通胀将在未来几年恢复到美联储 2% 的通胀目标。他们不同意<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/markets-appear-convinced-the-fed-can-pull-off-a-soft-landing-700a40dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">投资者最近的乐观看法</a>，即通胀可以在不出现更广泛的经济放缓的情况下持续缓解，尽管他们承认即将公布的数据可能会增强人们对美联储能够实现所谓软着陆的希望，即在不让经济陷入衰退的情况下遏制价格压力。</p><p>其中许多经济学家担心工资增长过于强劲。如果没有经济衰退，他们预计<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americans-working-job-market-prime-age-9fdc339b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">劳动力市场紧张</a>将推高明年的核心通胀。</p><p>由于劳动力市场过热可能首先体现在工资上，许多人将工资增长视为潜在通胀压力的良好指标。</p><p>假设生产率每年增长约 1% 至 1.5%，官员们可能会看到年工资增长率为 3.5%，与 2% 至 2.5% 之间的通胀率一致。</p><p>根据劳工部的就业成本指数，1月至3月期间工资和薪金同比增长5%。美联储密切关注该指数，因为它是衡量工资增长的最全面指标。第二季度数据将于7月28日公布。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822099?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一些经济学家认为，有充分证据表明劳动力市场正在降温。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：jim lo scalzo/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>自上而下与自下而上</h3><p>一个大问题是，在劳动力市场吃紧的情况下，在工资跟不上通货膨胀的两年后，工人是否会接受经通货膨胀调整后的最低工资增长。</p><p>波士顿联储前行长埃里克·罗森格伦 (Eric Rosengren) 表示：“大多数人在得知明年工资将上涨 3.5% 后，至少会考虑，‘如果我去其他地方，我能得到更高的工资吗？’”</p><p>一个相关的担忧是：许多投资者对通胀的乐观分析——一种自下而上的观点，强调二手车价格即将下降和租金急剧放缓——近年来却产生了糟糕的预测。</p><p>迪南表示，两年前，经济学家认为特殊且急剧的价格上涨将迅速逆转，这导致他们忽视了强劲的潜在需求。</p><p>她说：“2021 年的经历有力地提醒我们，关注特殊故事而不是更深层次的潜在力量是存在风险的。” “你仍然必须回到大局，认识到今天有很多潜在的动力。”</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MS" class="">摩根士丹利</a>首席全球经济学家塞斯·卡彭特表示，传统的自上而下的经济分析可能会认为某些价格类别的通胀下降，以减轻可支配收入的压力，刺激需求并造成更大的通胀压力<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><h3>劳动力市场松动的一些迹象</h3><p>第二阵营经济学家认为，有充分证据表明劳动力市场正在降温，从而减轻了通胀压力。</p><p>失业工人寻找新工作所需的时间一直在增加。私营部门雇员的工作时间增长随着空缺职位数量的增加而放缓。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBS" class="">瑞银集团</a>首席美国经济学家乔纳森·平格尔表示：“这表明劳动力市场确实正在放缓<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ”</p><p>今年上半年，私营部门每月平均招聘职位数降至 215,000 个，低于 2022 年下半年的 317,000 个和 2022 年上半年的 436,000 个。但我们正在努力解决这个问题，”经济学家、纽约联储前高管布莱恩·萨克(Brian Sack)表示。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为明年通胀率会回到2%吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>如果就业市场继续每月增加 20 万个职位，“这就是美联储在更长时间内保持较高水平的许可，”平格尔在谈到利率水平时表示。但如果就业增长继续放缓，同时通胀下降推高实际利率，“他们将面临更激烈的权衡，决定他们想要的限制程度。”</p><p> 6 月份，美联储官员预计，他们需要在当前水平上再加息两次 25 个基点，而 3 月份预计不会进一步加息。他们还预计今年通胀将放缓。</p><p> “认为我们需要两次加息的观点部分是因为他们对通胀没有大幅放缓感到沮丧。现在情况正在改变，”萨克说。 “The rate hike this week is more strongly justified by the robustness of growth and hiring than the incoming data on inflation.”</p><p> Officials can debate whether that second move is necessary if inflation and economic activity continue to slow. “The encouraging news about inflation is creating space for the Fed to be more patient and take their time,” Dynan said.</p><p> Write to Nick Timiraos at <a href="mailto:Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 21:16:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-fed-isnt-ready-to-declare-victory-on-inflation-e882b4d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-fed-isnt-ready-to-declare-victory-on-inflation-e882b4d9<author><![CDATA[Nick Timiraos]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category> Monetary Policy</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>Economic Predictions/Forecasts</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>摩根士丹利</category><category>多发性硬化症</category><category>瑞银集团</category><category>UBS</category><category> Karen Dynan</category><category> Seth Carpenter</category><category>经济表现</category><category>indicators</category><category> inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>economic predictions</category><category> forecasts </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hidden Career Cost of Being Overweight]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> New moves to outlaw weight discrimination are pushing companies to examine one of the most insidious forms of on-the-job bias <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074681"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821735?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WSJ; ISTOCK(3) </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ray A. Smith</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 24, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Looking back, Michelle Matthews said she often internalized co-workers&#39; comments about her weight. At one work lunch, a teammate remarked on how much she was eating. A higher-up told her she needed to “show up physically as a leader” after she failed to win a promotion.</p><p> It wasn&#39;t until the tech-product design director switched to remote work in 2020 that she grasped how much such slights had colored her office career.</p><p> “I didn&#39;t realize how much I was thinking about my physicality,” said Matthews, 38, who describes herself as a big person. “It took up a lot of my mind.”</p><p> Weight stigma is rarely talked about at work, but it pervades workplaces everywhere, employees and hiring managers say. <a href="https://www.stlouisfed.org/publications/regional-economist/october-2011/worth-your-weight-reexamining-the-link-between-obesity-and-wages#:~:text=Economist%20John%20Cawley%20estimates%20that%20overweight%20and%20obese,percent%20less%2C%20respectively%2C%20than%20normal%20weight%20white%20women." target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Study after study</a> shows heavier people are paid and <a href="https://www.employment-studies.co.uk/system/files/resources/files/526.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">promoted less</a> than thinner colleagues and are often stereotyped as <a href="https://sloanreview.mit.edu/article/the-opportunity-costs-of-weight-bias-at-work/" target="_blank" class="icon none">lazy or undisciplined</a> . In a spring survey of more than 1,000 human-resources executives, 11% said an applicant&#39;s weight had factored into hiring decisions. Half of managers surveyed in a separate poll said they preferred interacting with “healthy-weight” employees, according to SHRM, the human resources professional network that conducted the surveys. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Diabetes drugs could become an effective way to treat behavioral issues and addiction. WSJ&#39;s Daniela Hernandez breaks down the science on how they work and how they could change psychiatry forever. Photo illustration: Elizabeth Smelov<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Now, as New York City and some states move to outlaw weight discrimination at work, companies are beginning to focus on the experience of overweight workers. Many managers are unprepared for the wave of complaints the legislation could bring, advocates for the laws say.</p><p> Weight “is still not looked at from a [diversity and inclusion] perspective,” says Jessica Richman, founder of the Visible Collective, a group that advises companies on supporting workers and consumers who are considered obese.</p><h3> New legal pressure</h3><p> Signed into law in May, the New York City ban adds weight and height to the list of characteristics protected from discrimination, alongside race, gender, age, religion and sexual orientation. Several states, including New Jersey and Massachusetts, have introduced similar bills. (Michigan is currently the only state to prohibit employment discrimination on the basis of weight. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821633?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tech leaders such as Amazon&#39;s Jeff Bezos have been subject to scrutiny over their physiques.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: chandan khanna/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Nearly two-thirds of employers haven&#39;t addressed weight-related stereotyping or bias with their employees, according to SHRM. Though a small number of employers, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> have formed employee groups to support overweight workers and raise awareness of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/schools-relax-dress-codes-in-bid-to-end-body-shaming-11563010202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“fat-shaming,”</a> they remain the exception.</p><p> Even business leaders who have been vocal advocates of inclusive workplaces say they have given little thought to weight biases until recently.</p><p> “It wasn&#39;t on my radar,” said Jonathan Mildenhall, co-founder and chair of global brand consulting firm TwentyFirstCenturyBrand, who says his company and its corporate clients will have to give the issue more attention. Employers may also need to reconsider workplace <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-your-company-need-to-know-your-body-mass-index-11549902536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">weight-loss challenges</a> or other programs and benefits, including reimbursement for drugs <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-want-ozempic-for-weight-loss-few-employers-want-to-pay-for-it-215fb5c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">such as Ozempic</a> , he said.</p><h3> Business leaders get buff</h3><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">body-positivity movement</a> that championed fat acceptance, plus-size fashion models and extended clothing sizes over the past decade helped fuel the recent weight-discrimination legislation. Now, the rise of Ozempic, Wegovy and similar treatments may lead some people to conclude obesity is a choice if losing weight is a matter of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-housewife-isnt-on-ozempic-how-a-weight-loss-craze-is-shaping-reality-tv-afb21602?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking a drug</a> .</p><p> Pressure to be fit is already intense for anyone aspiring to rise through the management ranks, some executives say. The internet is awash in images and reports of how tech leaders such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/jeff-bezos">Jeff Bezos</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg</a> achieved their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ceo-workout-abs-bezos-musk-11662166439?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">now-buff physiques</a> . And some leadership coaches say staying trim is virtually <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324595704578241573341483946?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a requirement</a> for getting on the CEO track.</p><p> Keith Wolf, managing partner of recruiting firm Murray Resources in Houston, said he has never heard a corporate client cite a job candidate&#39;s weight for deciding against them. But it would be naive to think appearance isn&#39;t a factor. “You can just kind of look at who actually is hired for certain roles,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822358?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Former IBM Chief Executive Ginni Rometty said in a memoir that she was encouraged to lose weight to get ahead.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alex Kraus/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Companies, he added, are “worried about how leaders are perceived and everything they do, how they dress, how they show up in meetings.”</p><p> In her recent memoir “Good Power,” former <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IBM" class="company-name">IBM</a> Chief Executive Ginni Rometty recounted how, earlier in her career, when she had put on weight, a boss suggested trimming down would help her get ahead.</p><p> Take a look at other high-level executives, and “most seem to be in good physical shape,” he pointed out to her.</p><p></p> Michael Hearn, a 59-year-old information technology program manager, says he has been overweight for much of his career. When he sought informal feedback as to why he was passed over for promotions, “they would say, &#39;Everyone knows you&#39;re a smart guy, everybody knows you work hard. You just don&#39;t present well because of your size,&#39;” he said.<p></p><p> He lost 200 pounds in recent years and has since left his job while he plots a career reset, he said.</p><h3> Remote-work revelations</h3><p> Remote work has transformed daily life for some people who are overweight. Matthews, the tech product design director, said she didn&#39;t worry as much about what to wear or her physical presence once she began working from home in 2020. When on-screen, she could angle the camera in ways that flattered or played down her figure.</p><p> New job opportunities opened up, which she partly attributes to working and interviewing virtually. She landed a role in 2021 as a director of product design at a healthcare company, and later, a promotion to senior director.</p><p> “The course of my career really changed when I went remote,” she said.</p><p> Weight discrimination cases rarely succeed. Some workers have filed suits invoking the Americans with Disabilities Act, which protects job candidates and employees from discrimination, harassment or retaliation because of a disability. Most courts have held that obesity isn&#39;t a disability under the ADA unless it is caused by an underlying health condition. The Texas Supreme Court said as much in a <a href="https://www.txcourts.gov/media/1456743/220179.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">ruling in June</a> , when it decided against a medical resident who alleged she had been fired from Texas Tech University Health Sciences Center because of her obesity.</p><p> Some companies have formed employee groups to raise awareness of fat bias. Amazon&#39;s Body Positive Peers, formed in 2020, often uses its meetings and blog posts to highlight the corrosive effects of fat-shaming and ways to make the company&#39;s products and services more size inclusive.</p><p> JAMS, a global provider of dispute-resolution services, launched a similar employee group two years ago. Its HR chief, Tracy Curry, says its existence helps signal to hires that the company cares about the challenges overweight workers can face.</p><p> Karen Pavlin, chief equity and inclusion officer of business-software company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NOW" class="">ServiceNow</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> said the new New York City law has prompted her to think more about weight as part of the company&#39;s diversity efforts, especially in light of data showing Black and Latina women have a disproportionately high obesity risk.</p><p> ServiceNow&#39;s TruAbility group, which advocates for employees with disabilities, also addresses issues around body size, Pavlin says. She expects other companies will follow with similar employee groups.</p><p> “It&#39;s long overdue,” she said.</p><p> Write to Ray A. Smith at <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hidden-career-cost-of-being-overweight-68f4b8e7<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>管理</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>歧视</category><category>Physical/Mental Fitness</category><category>健康</category><category>Human Rights/Civil Liberties</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category>社会问题</category><category>体重管理</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>管理</category><category>labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>career planning</category><category>歧视</category><category>身体的</category><category>mental fitness</category><category> health</category><category> human rights</category><category> civil liberties</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>living</category><category>生活方式</category><category>社会问题</category><category>weight management</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Parents Hire $4,000 Sorority Consultants to Help Daughters Dress and Impress During Rush]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Getting into sororities is nearly as tough as entry to top universities; &#39;Be trendy but not too trendy, modest but not too modest, fit in but be unique&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820654/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="去年，Phi Mu 的新成员前往位于阿拉巴马州塔斯卡卢萨的阿拉巴马大学与联谊会姐妹会面。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> New members of Phi Mu en route to meeting with their sorority sisters last year at the University of Alabama in Tuscaloosa, Ala. Will McLelland/USA TODAY NETWORK/Reuters <span>Will McLelland/USA TODAY NETWORK/Reuters</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074760"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074760"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Tara Weiss</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 24, 2023 8:05 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Sorority rush at the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-bulldogs-college-football-playoff-champions-11673323071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">University of Georgia</a> kicks off in August, a lousy time to wear makeup.</p><p> “You need to do it in a way that&#39;s appropriate in southern humidity or else you&#39;re going to have orange rivers running down your face,” said Trisha Addicks. She recommends keeping a “rush bag” with deodorant, portable fan, water and face powder.</p><p> That&#39;s the kind of practical advice Addicks gives clients of her Georgia-based sorority-consulting firm, It&#39;s All Greek to Me. Showing up in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/DOCS" class="company-name">Dr. Martens</a> combat boots, as one client asked about, might not be putting your best foot forward in some <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-house-design-in-the-age-of-instagram-and-rushtok-11672263322?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sorority circles</a> , she said: “During rush, you&#39;re not going to be confident if you&#39;re wearing them, and everybody else is wearing espadrilles.”</p><p> Addicks offers a $600 seminar for women and their mothers to learn the basics about getting into a sorority; $3,500 buys unlimited access to sorority mentors who advise aspirants through every step. She is part of an industry emerging in recent years that sells tips and emotional support to women who want to avoid missteps that threaten first impressions. Sorority consultants cover such topics as what to wear, how to act, what to say and the wisdom of scrubbing potentially off-putting social media posts. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820474?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Shannon Rust, in an outfit curated by her sorority consultant, at the University of Georgia in Athens, Ga., during rush.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Elizabeth Payne</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Emma Kelley, a recent graduate, said hiring Addicks was worth it. Otherwise, she risked entering blind to the arcane rituals, traditions and unspoken rules of Greek life. “You have to be trendy but not too trendy, modest but not too modest, fit in but be unique,” said Kelley, who joined the University of Georgia&#39;s Delta Zeta sorority. The trick, she said, is “blending in and standing out.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820472?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Stacia Damron, founder and CEO of Hiking in Heels.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bridgette Bloomquist Photography</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Getting into sororities has become nearly as competitive as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/youre-about-to-pay-300-000-for-college-whats-another-3-000-in-campus-swag-9a2644eb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">acceptance to top universities.</a> Applicants are asked to write essays, give their grade-point average and report whether they did volunteer work or played high-school sports. Women submit application packets with as many as 30 letters of recommendation, said Stacia Damron, owner of Hiking in High Heels in Texas. Some sororities require that applicants record video responses to their questions. “My boyfriend went to Stanford, and he said this is more complicated than getting a Stanford MBA,” she said.</p><p> Damron tells clients that they need a social-media presence but warns that sorority members will scour a recruit&#39;s posts. She suggests that women erase images of themselves in very skimpy outfits or with alcohol. Instead, they should pile up posts about family, friends, hobbies and volunteer work. “It&#39;s about telling a story to help the sororities get to know you,” said Damron. Her fees run as high as $4,000 for on-call service during rush. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1014" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822501?width=639&amp;height=1014" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sorority consultant Trisha Addicks</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Paige Molina Photography, Atlanta</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Leighton Newberry, owner of Recruitment Ready in Atlanta, said she spends a lot of time prepping young women for conversation. All the hours young people spend texting and communicating over social media has left many inexperienced with face-to-face chitchat, she said. Newberry, who graduated from Auburn University in 2019, advises her clients to make eye contact and stay engaged with new acquaintances during rush season&#39;s many social events. She suggests asking questions: <em>Where are you from? Why did you pick this school to attend?</em></p><p> Newberry has a la carte sessions that cost $150 for video calls and $175 for in-person meetings. She also sells the Bid Day Bundle for $1,000. That includes three one-on-one sessions and assistance writing résumés and cover letters, as well as styling tips. She also gives frank talk about disappointment.</p><p> “You&#39;re not going to get what you want all the time,” Newberry said. “These are life skills that can carry with them for years to come. It&#39;s not just about getting into one sorority.”</p><p> Last year, 125,000 women sought a spot in sororities at the 500 campuses that provide data to the National Panhellenic Conference, and between a quarter and a fifth of them either quit or didn&#39;t get accepted, according to Dani Weatherford, chief executive of the conference, a trade group that represents sororities. Generally, sororities conduct four rounds of meetings with applicants and winnow the group after each round.</p><p> The $2,000 Fabulous and Chic package from Greek Chic in Manhattan provides four sessions on applications, social media and wardrobe, along with &#39;round-the-clock counseling during rush week. Owner Lorie Stefanelli recalled being at a rooftop concert when she got a call from a distraught client at the University of Texas, Austin. The young woman, in tears, had successfully passed several rounds but felt too exhausted to keep going. Stefanelli said she left the concert to soothe her client, telling her she was doing a great job and encouraging her to continue. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820473?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Women lining up for a sorority tour last year at the University of Nebraska in Lincoln, Neb.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Noah Riffe/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Shannon Rust had to bounce back from a few rejections after leaving home in Stamford, Conn., to attend the University of Georgia last year. She had known little about sororities, and her roommate&#39;s mother suggested Addicks, of It&#39;s All Greek to Me. Shannon&#39;s mother, Janine Rust,</p> said she first thought that the idea of paying for a sorority consultant was crazy. But she went ahead and hired Addicks.<p></p><p> Rust said that after Shannon called her to say she had been cut from several sororities, she was more upset than her daughter was. “How could they not want my kid,” Rust recalled thinking. Then she picked up the phone and got consoled by Addicks.</p><p> “Having someone to be able to call 24/7 to talk me off the ledge was immeasurable,” Rust said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 12:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sorority-consultants-rush-colleges-parents-prepare-80b2cfc8<category> a-hed</category><category> Cosmetics/Toiletries</category><category>护肤品</category><category>鞋类</category><category>Retail/Wholesale</category><category> Clothing Retail</category><category> Specialty Retailing</category><category> Beauty/Personal Care</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Body Care Products</category><category> Clothing/Textiles</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category>护发产品</category><category>Personal Care Products/Appliances</category><category> Personal Care Accessories</category><category>零售</category><category>Specialized Consumer Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学学院</category><category>Selection of Top Stories/Trends/Analysis</category><category> Suggested Reading – Industry News</category><category> Suggested Reading – Accounting/Consulting</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>selection of top stories</category><category>趋势</category><category>分析</category><category>suggested reading – industry news</category><category> suggested reading – accounting</category><category>咨询</category><category>化妆品</category><category>化妆品</category><category>护肤品</category><category>鞋类</category><category>retail</category><category>批发的</category><category>clothing retail</category><category> specialty retailing</category><category>美丽</category><category>personal care</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>身体护理产品</category><category>衣服</category><category>纺织品</category><category>consumer goods</category><category>护发产品</category><category>个人护理产品</category><category>电器</category><category>personal care accessories</category><category> specialized consumer services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Spanish Elections Point to Lengthy Coalition Talks—and Maybe a Revote]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Voters flocked to centrist parties—but the election failed to produce a clear winner <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073435"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822362?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，人们在巴塞罗那的一家酒吧观看有关选举结果的新闻。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：琼·马特乌·帕拉/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073435"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">何塞·包蒂斯塔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 24, 2023 6:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-votes-in-election-that-could-signal-shift-to-the-right-123e49e2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>西班牙全国选举未能产生明显多数，没有任何政治力量在议会中获得足够的席位来组建政府，这一结果可能会导致大小政党之间长期的联合谈判。</p><p>西班牙选民纷纷涌向主要的中右翼和中左翼政党，但不足以给予其中任何一个明确的授权。结果如此接近，执政党社会党和反对党人民党都有机会组建新政府。也有可能无法获得多数票，西班牙人将被要求重返投票站。</p><p>根据最终结果，中右翼人民党（PP）在下议院赢得了约 38% 的席位，高于任何其他政党，但低于民意调查的预期。即使得到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/far-right-looks-to-seize-on-spanish-election-919439b4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">极右翼 Vox 党</a>（其最有可能的联盟伙伴）的支持，人民党领导的政府也无法获得议会多数席位。</p><p>由社会党总理佩德罗·桑切斯领导的中左翼联盟（包括左翼团体苏马尔）也未能获得多数席位。社会党比上次选举增加了选票份额，获得了约 34% 的议会席位。</p><p>如果桑切斯能够与几个地区政党建立联盟，或者说服他们支持少数派政府，他可能会继续掌权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822363?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">选举官员周日在潘普洛纳的一个投票站清点选票。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔瓦罗·巴里恩托斯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>可能成为国王拥护者的小党派包括加泰罗尼亚团结组织，这是一个由卡尔斯·普伊格德蒙特领导的分离主义组织。五年前，普伊格德蒙特在组织了一场非法的公投，要求富裕地区独立后逃离了西班牙。该党在周日的选举中排名第五，赢得众议院七个席位。</p><p> “Spain is one of the few remaining countries in Europe that still has strong social democrats and strong conservatives,” says José Ignacio Torreblanca, a Madrid-based political analyst at the European Council on Foreign Relations.</p><p>他补充说：“大多数西班牙人都投票给中间派政党，但谁能组建政府的结果却被少数选票和政治光谱极端的政党所左右。”</p><p>桑切斯执政五年后，他的左翼联盟在五月的地方和地区选举中惨败，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spanish-leader-calls-snap-vote-after-governing-socialists-suffer-losses-in-local-election-db7d8ac8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">呼吁提前举行全国选举</a>。</p><p>桑切斯通过有效的疫苗接种活动带领西班牙度过了 Covid-19 大流行。他的政府比大多数欧洲国家更成功地保护了经济免受乌克兰战争引发的能源危机的影响，并成功地<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-long-does-inflation-anger-linger-spanish-voters-may-have-the-answer-c8100cda?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将通货膨胀率</a>从一年前的峰值 10.7% 降至 6 月份的 1.6%，低于欧洲平均水平。</p><p>然而，对去年生活成本上涨的愤怒情绪依然挥之不去。 Sánchez also faces criticism for his reliance on small, pro-independence parties in Catalonia and the Basque Country—parties he may have to turn to once again if he wants to try to form a government. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="471" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822364?width=700&amp;height=471" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">社会党总理佩德罗·桑切斯周日在马德里社会党总部庆祝。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：哈维尔·索里亚诺/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822365?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">人民党领导人阿尔贝托·努涅斯·费约 (Alberto Núñez Feijóo) 经常表示，他希望避免与 Vox 结盟。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：胡安·梅迪纳/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>选举前，民意调查显示 PP-Vox 政府是最有可能的结果。这将标志着西班牙的一个转折点，因为它将首次让民族主义和反移民政党 Vox 进入政府，其成员包括已故西班牙独裁者弗朗西斯科·佛朗哥的支持者。</p><p>桑切斯周日晚上表示：“我之所以呼吁提前选举，是因为我相信我们作为一个社会必须决定采取什么路线，是进步的路线还是倒退的路线。” “西班牙及其所有公民的态度非常明确。落后的倒退集团提议彻底废除我们过去四年取得的所有进步，但已经失败了。”</p><p>新议会将于八月中旬召开。</p><p> Vox&#39;s strident rhetoric against migrants, its hostility to the LGBTQ community and its denial of man-made climate change are among the issues that many of the PP&#39;s leaders and voters find distasteful.人民党领导人阿尔贝托·努涅斯·费霍 (Alberto Núñez Feijóo) 经常表示，他希望避免与 Vox 结盟。这并没有阻止巴伦西亚和埃斯特雷马杜拉等地区的人民党领导人在最近的地方选举后与 Vox 组成执政联盟。</p><p> “As the candidate of the most voted party, I believe it is my duty to start and lead a dialogue to try to govern our country,” Feijóo told supporters after the vote count.</p><p> The prospect of Vox entering government with the PP also spooked centrist and leftist voters—and may help explain why the Socialists fared better than expected. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822367?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西班牙 Vox 党的支持者在马德里 Vox 党总部外等待选举结果。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：文森特·韦斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>来自沿海城市巴伦西亚的 40 岁屠夫何塞·弗朗西斯科·西蒙 (José Francisco Simón) 决定投票支持社会党，部分原因是他想阻止极右翼上台。</p><p>他说，人民党“将与极右翼组成联盟”。 “我还年轻，我不想回到 1960 年”，指的是佛朗哥政权。</p><p> Vox的表现比预期要差得多，在众议院赢得了33个席位，比上次选举少了19个。</p><p> 61 岁的经济学家特立尼达·科尔内霍 (Trinidad Cornejo) 并不担心 PP-Vox 可能结盟，他在周日投票支持了 PP。事实上，她希望人民党能够承担 Vox 的一些立场，例如呼吁减少地区的治理自主权。</p><p> “西班牙人担心国家层面没有统一的卫生和教育系统，因为这些都是地区性的，”科尔内霍说。 “这在国家造成了不平等，我认为 Vox 在这方面的立场并不是极右。”</p><p>写信给玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂： <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 10:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-votes-in-election-that-c​​ould-signal-shift-to-the-right-123e49e2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-votes-in-election-that-c​​ould-signal-shift-to-the-right-123e49e2<author><![CDATA[Margherita Stancati]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Elections</category><category> National/Presidential Elections</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>佩德罗·桑切斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>presidential elections </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Corruption Hunters Target Produce Aisle in Push for Seed Security]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Campaign reflects Xi Jinping&#39;s growing concern over food security as tensions simmer with US <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073164"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="378" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821884?width=700&amp;height=378" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China aims to stop the proliferation of fake and substandard seeds that could jeopardize food production and safety.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073164"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chun Han Wong</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 24, 2023 6:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-corruption-hunters-target-produce-aisle-in-push-for-seed-security-1e854fda"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> For one of his newest <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-china-anticorruption-11665925166?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">anticorruption campaigns</a> , Chinese leader Xi Jinping is ordering his enforcers to dig up dirt. This time, he means, literally, the kind in the ground.</p><p> The Communist Party&#39;s top disciplinary body—after punishing graft in the military, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-jinping-tightens-grip-on-domestic-security-forces-in-first-broad-purge-11597773887?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">domestic security organs</a> and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-scrutinizes-chinese-financial-institutions-ties-with-private-firms-11633972484?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">financial sector</a> —is now hunting officials, merchants and farmers it suspects of harvesting illicit profits from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-looks-to-secure-supplies-as-strains-with-u-s-and-its-allies-grow-11642075381?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">trade in grains and seeds</a> . The body is one of the busiest and most powerful agencies in China, tasked with imposing control in areas that Xi considers his top priorities.</p><p> Tasked with being more forceful in safeguarding the nation&#39;s “seed security,” authorities have investigated dozens of cases involving seed-related misconduct and, in several instances, imprisoned grain-sector officials on corruption charges, according to government disclosures and state media reports. Meanwhile, local governments are directing their own crackdowns on “seed sector corruption,” sending cadres into the countryside to educate farmers and flush out offenders.</p><p> Senior Chinese lawmakers also are reviewing a proposed food security law, which would set legal frameworks for safeguarding food production and supplies, developing cutting-edge seed technologies and punishing misconduct that jeopardizes food safety and national security, according to a draft issued in late June by China&#39;s national legislature.</p><p> Officials say the goal is to stop the proliferation of fake and substandard seeds that could jeopardize food production and safety, while punishing officials, merchants and farmers who siphon agricultural subsidies and peddle low-grade seeds.</p><p> Xi has often highlighted <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/china-xi-jinping-communist-party-congress/card/china-s-security-concerns-often-start-with-its-stomach-xBLvDsSDwc0j4jg7s5wL?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">food security as a national interest</a> , calling on officials to ensure that China can fully nourish its 1.4 billion people. His demands have taken on greater urgency in recent years as he pushed to prepare his country for a potential confrontation with the US—a major source of Chinese grain imports, including soybeans and corn—and forestall disruptions to food supplies for one of the world&#39;s most populous nations. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="545" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822238?width=700&amp;height=545" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China must develop independence and strength in seed technology, President Xi Jinping said while visiting a seed laboratory in Hainan province in 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Xie Huanchi/Xinhua/ZUMA PRESS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> China&#39;s rulers since ancient times have regarded food security as a cornerstone of social stability, with food shortages and famines often triggering uprisings. The Communist Party has also been preoccupied with this issue, particularly after confronting its own crisis during the great famine of 1959-1961, when tens of millions of people are estimated to have starved to death following Mao Zedong&#39;s radical attempts to collectivize agriculture and rapidly industrialize the country.</p><p> Today, Beijing sees the seed sector as one of several strategic industries where Western powers could flex their technological superiority to strangle a lagging China. Demonstrating his personal interest in this field, Xi has twice visited a seed-breeding base in the island province of Hainan that officials call the “Silicon Valley” of China&#39;s seed industry.</p><p> “If the Chinese people want to hold their rice bowls firmly in their own hands, they must grasp their seeds firmly in their own hands,” Xi said while touring the base last year. This means, he said, that China must develop independence and strength in seed technology, and “use Chinese seeds to guarantee China&#39;s food security.”</p><p> China is the world&#39;s largest grain producer, growing one-quarter of global supply on less than 10% of the world&#39;s arable land. But its ability to feed its own people has slipped over recent decades by some estimates. Last year, a former deputy chief of China&#39;s top economic-planning agency said the country&#39;s food self-sufficiency rate—or the percentage of nutritional needs that can be met by homegrown crops—has fallen to roughly 76% from about 100% in 2000, a drop that he attributed to China&#39;s declining competitiveness in agricultural output and the relative weakness of its seed industry.</p><p> While China&#39;s agricultural sector has attained a high degree of self-sufficiency using domestically sourced seeds, with imports accounting for only 0.1% of seeds consumed in the country, “there is still a lot of room for improvement” in Chinese seed-breeding technology and output, Wan Jianmin, deputy head of Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences, told a party newspaper in a 2021 interview. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821898?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Officials call the seed-breeding base in the island province of Hainan the &#39;Silicon Valley&#39; of China&#39;s seed industry.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Zhang Liyun/Xinhua/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Officials and state media have taken to comparing seeds to advanced semiconductor chips, a technology that China has pledged to master in its quest for a national renaissance. The late agronomist Yuan Longping,</p> for instance, has been feted as a national hero for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stubborn-rice-breeder-helped-end-hunger-in-china-11622210400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">developing higher-yielding hybrid varieties of rice</a> that helped production catch up with demand. But the agricultural sector has also been plagued by corruption and fraud, which can threaten national interests.<p></p><p> “Seeds, as the &#39;chips&#39; of agriculture, aren&#39;t just a new racetrack in the technological competition between various countries, but are also an important bargaining chip in the game between great powers,” the state-run Farmers&#39; Daily said in a recent front-page commentary.</p><p> While China&#39;s seed industry is strong enough to survive foreign strangulation, the country still falls behind in seed quality, according to the Farmers&#39; Daily, which recommended measures including “resolutely cracking down” on the trading of fake and mislabeled seeds, whereby officials and merchants defraud farmers with counterfeit or lower-grade goods marked as top-quality seeds.</p><p> While state regulators and academies increase seed-related research, party and government enforcers are focusing on policing industry behavior. In January, the party&#39;s top disciplinary agency said corruption remained rampant in China&#39;s food-supply chain and issued a directive demanding more enforcement pressure to curb shady deals related to grain trading.</p><p> To hammer home the message, the party published a new anthology of Xi&#39;s remarks on “national food security,” while the official newspaper of the party&#39;s top disciplinary agency zeroed in on the seed sector in a recent front-page article, which described seed production and sales as a lucrative trade where cadres can be led astray by the promise of easy money.</p><p> The newspaper cited a case where a seed company paid more than 80 local officials to sell substandard seeds across nearly 30 villages in the southwestern province of Sichuan, causing “severe losses for farmers” who found that the seeds germinated at a rate far below state benchmarks. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821896?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A researcher conducting hybrid-rice experiments as China seeks to improve the quality and yield of its produce.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Zhang Liyun/Xinhua/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Authorities have also sought to deter seed-related corruption by publicizing investigations into alleged offenders. One such probe took down Su Jiaqian, a local agricultural official in the eastern province of Zhejiang, who was expelled from the party in September before a local court sentenced him to three years and 10 months in prison on corruption charges.</p><p> The government said Su accepted bribes valued at the equivalent of about $20,000 between 2014 and 2017 from farmers who benefited from subsidies that he approved. Su felt justified in taking gifts to compensate for expenses that he couldn&#39;t get reimbursed for, according to the government&#39;s account. Su was also accused of collaborating with others to defraud the government of agricultural subsidies valued at the equivalent of more than $121,000, the account said.</p><p> Instead of devoting himself to local agriculture, the local party disciplinary commission said, Su allowed “the &#39;seed&#39; of corruption to eat up his original aspirations, and in the end, he can only reap what he sowed.”</p><p> Su couldn&#39;t be reached for comment. The official account of his case didn&#39;t say how he pleaded at trial, and his case couldn&#39;t be found in the state-run online court document repository.</p><p> Seed-security propaganda efforts have been especially robust in Anhui, a province in central eastern China known for its agricultural output. In the Anhui city of Bozhou, a major producer of wheat, corn and soybeans, officials have been required to attend screenings of a political education film titled “The Bottom Line of Seed Security Can&#39;t Be Touched.”</p><p> “To the people, food is of the utmost importance,” the provincial disciplinary commission quoted a Bozhou party inspector as saying. “When it comes to food, seeds are fundamental.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821921?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mourners at the 2021 funeral of agronomist Yuan Longping, feted as a national hero for developing higher-yielding hybrid varieties of rice that boosted production.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Xue Yuge/Xinhua/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Chun Han Wong at <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-corruption-hunters-target-produce-aisle-in-push-for-seed-security-1e854fda</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-corruption-hunters-target-produce-aisle-in-push-for-seed-security-1e854fda<author><![CDATA[Chun Han Wong]]></author><category>农业</category><category>农业</category><category>Oilseed/Grain Farming</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Corruption</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Food/Drinking Water Security</category><category> Financial Crime</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Welfare/Social Services</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>腐败</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>食物</category><category>drinking water security</category><category> financial crime</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>welfare</category><category> social services</category><category>农业</category><category>农业</category><category>油籽</category><category>grain farming </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Chinese Money Flees the Western World]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>曾经购买纽约市酒店的投资者正在将资金投向其他地方<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073569"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821864?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据估计，镍资源丰富的印度尼西亚是今年迄今为止中国投资的最大接受国。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Hariandi Hafid/SOPA Images/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073569"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">：谢一凡</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 24, 2023 2:29 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-money-flees-the-western-world-673d9bbb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>就在几年前，中国的资金正在席卷富裕世界。中国投资者正在进行重磅交易并抢购炫耀性资产，从纽约的豪华住宅和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-yorks-waldorf-astoria-hotel-finds-a-rocky-path-to-condo-conversion-11651492804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">五星级酒店</a>到一家瑞士化工公司和一家德国机器人巨头。</p><p>那个时代已经结束了。</p><p>随着西方对中国资本的敌意加剧，中国投资正在从西方撤退。随着北京寻求巩固在这些地区的联盟并确保获得关键资源，中国企业越来越多地将资金投入东南亚的工厂以及亚洲、中东和南美洲的采矿和能源项目。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823037?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>根据保守派智库美国企业研究所编制的对中国投资的初步估计，《华尔街日报》看到，今年迄今为止中国投资的最大接受国是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-china-came-to-dominate-the-worlds-largest-nickel-source-for-electric-cars-4c081a12?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">镍资源丰富的印度尼西亚</a>。镍是许多电动汽车电池的关键成分。</p><p>投资流向的转变表明，中国正在如何应对与美国领导的西方关系恶化，并正在加强与世界其他地区的贸易和投资联系，其方式可能会在全球经济中造成新的断层线。</p><p>中国资金撤回西方可能会导致一些国家创造的就业机会减少，同时也会减少硅谷等地企业家可以利用的资本池。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-many-in-china-it-feels-like-a-recession-25ce4b68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国疲弱的经济</a>已经让世界失去了传统的增长引擎之一。</p><p>更广泛地说，这种转变表明全球化正在衰退，地缘政治紧张局势更有可能加剧。</p><p>最近发布的一项新措施显示，中国对世界其他地区的直接海外投资同比下降了18%。由于海外并购大幅下降以及北京收紧了遏制<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/big-chinese-deals-stall-on-capital-outflows-clampdown-1485563072?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">资本外逃</a>的规定，最新水平较 2016 年的峰值下降了 25%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821854?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2015 年，纽约市的华尔道夫酒店 (Waldorf Astoria) 以 19.5 亿美元的价格出售给一家中国保险公司。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯西·威伦斯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管北京去年放松了对Covid-19的限制，但中国不太可能回到海外交易的鼎盛时期，这在很大程度上是因为与美国及其盟国的地缘政治紧张局势不断加剧，据分析人士称，美国及其盟国正在以国家安全为由阻止更多的中国投资。</p><p>分析师补充说，在中国国内， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">货币贬值</a>、私营部门陷入困境，以及中国政府日益注重建设国内经济以增强自给自足，也将抑制其投资外流。</p><p>标准普尔全球评级首席亚太经济学家路易斯·奎伊斯表示：“总体而言，中国向外国发达经济体输送投资的空间正在缩小。”他表示，未来三到五年，中国海外投资流量不太可能大幅增加。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822215?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>相反，中国可能会重新调整投资，以巩固其在可再生能源和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rise-of-chinas-ev-makers-puts-end-to-wests-local-dominance-775d0811?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">电动汽车等领域的主导地位。</a>这可能意味着加倍加大对东南亚、中东和非洲等新兴市场的投资，因为中国工厂主正在寻找扩大经营和寻找新客户的地方，而北京则专注于资源丰富的市场。</p><p>中国汽车制造商比亚迪本月表示，计划在巴西的几家汽车工厂投资超过6亿美元。</p><p>美国企业研究所高级研究员德里克·史剑道(Derek Scissors)在谈到中国​​海外投资的高水位时表示，“只要习近平还活着，我们就不会回到2016年。”他表示，虽然美国经济不太可能太怀念中国资本，但对于澳大利亚、加拿大或匈牙利等较小的西方经济体来说，中国资本的撤退可能会更加痛苦。</p><p>中国向西方经济体提供的资金减少确实有一些好处。例如，它可以减少推高房地产价格的投机行为，就像在大流行之前加拿大、美国和澳大利亚等地所做的那样。</p><p>房地产研究公司 MSCI 实物资产首席经济学家吉姆·科斯特洛表示：“当他们购买它时，他们就改变了市场。” “他们让每个人都加大力度，出价更高。”</p><p>过去十年中期，中国投资者在纽约等市场引发了投机狂潮。 2015年，保险公司安邦以19.5亿美元收购了华尔道夫酒店，这是当时有记录以来最昂贵的美国酒店收购案。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AE4FD438-DEFB-4490-BCA9-546AECD44AF8&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinese-money-flees-the-western-world-673d9bbb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Nickel is an essential component of electric-vehicle batteries and Indonesia is by far the world&#39;s largest producer. A rare visit to one of its biggest nickel plants reveals the heavy environmental cost of mining and processing the metal. Photo: Ulet Ifansasti<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>安邦于 2018 年被政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-s-insurance-regulator-to-take-over-anbang-insurance-owner-of-the-waldorf-astoria-1519351766?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">接管，</a>不久其创始人因与欺诈和滥用权力有关的金融犯罪被判处 18 年监禁。将华尔道夫酒店改造成豪华公寓的计划尚未完成。</p><p>最近，全球的对外直接投资都在减弱，而不仅仅是来自中国。联合国贸易和发展会议的数据显示，由于通胀、衰退担忧和金融市场动荡导致投资搁置，包括美国在内的所有国家 2022 年对外投资同比下降 14%。</p><p>但中国的衰退幅度更大、持续时间更长，尤其是在发达经济体，这是经济与西方脱节的迹象。</p><p>联合国数据显示，2022年中国海外投资降至1470亿美元左右，同比下降18%。 2016 年达到峰值 1,960 亿美元。</p><p> 2016年之前，北京积极鼓励中国企业对外投资，以帮助扩大中国的经济影响力。海航集团和大连万达等企业集团向全球银行、连锁酒店和电影院注入了大量资金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821848?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2010 年代的交易包括将德国机器人制造商库卡 (Kuka) 出售给中国美的 (Midea)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：anna szilagyi/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这次收购热潮与 20 世纪 80 年代日本企业在美国及其他地区的一系列收购进行了比较，当时日本企业收购了钢铁厂、地标性酒店和电影制片厂。</p><p>然而，到了 2016 年，对资本外流和中国企业集团财务压力的担忧导致北京方面加强了资本管制，并加强了对企业交易的审查。</p><p>最近，随着与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/despite-yellen-u-s-china-decoupling-has-momentum-of-its-own-9389d6d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">以美国为首的西方国家</a>关系恶化，人们对中国收购的态度变得强硬。华盛顿及其盟友在国家安全、贸易和台湾等问题上与北京发生冲突。</p><p>此外，中国一直在重新考虑其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-belt-road-debt-11663961638?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“一带一路”倡议，</a>重点是在发展中国家建设基础设施。在数十亿美元的贷款出现问题后，官员们希望中国的银行对新项目采取更加谨慎的态度。</p><p> In 2016, Chinese companies and state-owned entities made 120 investments in the Group of Seven advanced economies, 63 of which were in the US, according to a database of Chinese projects overseas with a value of at least $95 million that is maintained by the American Enterprise Institute and the Heritage Foundation, another US-based conservative think tank. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821858?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">包括长城汽车在内的中国汽车制造商纷纷进行海外投资。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢克·杜格尔比/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>交易包括中国买家财团收购美国电脑打印机制造商利盟，以及将德国机器人制造商库卡出售给中国美的。</p><p> Last year, the database recorded just 13 Chinese investments in G-7 countries. 2016年，中国企业在七国集团投资840亿美元，约占中国海外投资总额的一半。</p><p>美国企业研究所数据库显示，2022年，七国集团经济体投资总额为74亿美元，仅占当年中国海外投资的18%。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>根据纽约研究公司荣鼎集团和柏林智库墨卡托中国研究中心的一份报告，中国对欧洲的外国直接投资到 2022 年将达到十年来的最低水平，相当于 88 亿美元。</p><p>电动汽车行业是吸引中国投资的罕见亮点，但其规模还不足以抵消其他地区交易量的萎缩。</p><p> “中国脆弱的经济形势和地缘政治压力使得投资不太可能反弹至 2010 年中期水平，”5 月份发表的报告的作者写道。</p><p>根据美国企业研究所数据库，去年中国企业和国有实体在亚洲、南美和中东的投资总额为 245 亿美元，比 2021 年增长 13%。交易包括中国国有石油巨头中海油在巴西的 19 亿美元投资以及汽车制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GWLLY" class="company-name">长城汽车</a>和比亚迪在泰国的投资。</p><p>据美国企业研究所初步估计，今年上半年，中国企业对外投资总额为295亿美元，这表明随着疫情消退，海外活动将小幅回升。</p><p>印度尼西亚因其丰富的战略矿产而成为最大的接收国，占总量的 17%，不过这一估计可能会随着有关投资准确时间的更多信息而改变。</p><p>写信给 Stella Yifan Xie <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（stella.xie@wsj.com）</a>和 Jason Douglas（ <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jason.douglas@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 06:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-money-flees-the-western-world-673d9bbb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-money-flees-the-western-world-673d9bbb<author><![CDATA[Stella Yifan XieJason Douglas]]></author><category> Chemicals</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>实物资产交易</category><category>Capacity/Facilities</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>设施空缺</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>资本流动/无形贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>中海油</category><category>0883.HK</category><category>港币:883</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>实物资产交易</category><category>容量</category><category>facilities</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>设施空缺</category><category>trade</category><category>外部支付</category><category>资本流动</category><category>无形贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>化学品</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cleaning Up ChatGPT Takes Heavy Toll on Human Workers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>肯尼亚的承包商表示，他们在 OpenAI 热门聊天机器人推出前筛选暴力和性虐待描述的努力给他们带来了创伤<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819976/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Richard Mathenge 领导的团队负责在内罗毕的 OpenAI 审核色情内容。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Richard Mathenge 领导的团队负责在内罗毕的 OpenAI 审核色情内容。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001064482"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001064482"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karen-hao" itemprop="url" rel="author">Karenhao</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Deepa Seetharaman</a></span> Natalia Jidovanu 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 24 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-openai-content-abusive-sexually-explicit-harassment-kenya-workers-on-human-workers-cf191483"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>肯尼亚内罗毕——ChatGPT 和其他新型人工智能聊天机器人有潜力取代人类从事从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-chatgpt-chatbot-workplace-call-centers-5cd2142a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">客户服务代表</a>到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-striking-writers-are-disrupting-hollywood-shoots-303706a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">编剧</a>等各种工作。</p><p>但就目前而言，该技术依赖于不同类型的人类劳动力。近年来，东非的低薪工人经常做出令人痛苦的努力，以防止聊天机器人技术吐出攻击性或怪诞的言论。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ChatGPT</a>建立在所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-ai-still-doesnt-know-how-to-do-11657891316?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大型语言模型</a>之上，这是一种功能强大的软件，通过从互联网上抓取的大量文本进行训练，以学习人类语言的模式。庞大的数据增强了它的能力，使其能够像类固醇的自动完成引擎一样工作。训练也会造成危险。如果有正确的提示，大型语言模型可以在互联网最黑暗部分的启发下生成大量有毒内容。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-sam-altman-artificial-intelligence-openai-b0e1c8c9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ChatGPT 的母公司、人工智能研究公司 OpenAI</a>多年来一直在努力解决这些问题。甚至在创建 ChatGPT 之前，它就雇佣了肯尼亚的工作人员来审查和分类从网上获得的、由人工智能本身生成的数千条图形文本段落。 《华尔街日报》查阅的文件显示，许多段落包含对暴力、骚扰、自残、强奸、儿童性虐待和兽交的描述。</p><p>该公司使用分类的段落构建了一个人工智能安全过滤器，最终部署该过滤器以限制 ChatGPT 向数千万用户暴露类似内容。</p><p> “这四个月的经历是我在公司工作以来最糟糕的经历，”肯尼亚工人之一亚历克斯·凯鲁(Alex Kairu)在接受采访时说。</p><p>文件显示，OpenAI 在两年多的时间里整合了庞大的全球专业人力管道，以使其最尖端的人工智能技术得以存在。这项工作大部分都是良性的，例如，教 ChatGPT 成为一个引人入胜的健谈者或诙谐的抒情者。人工智能研究人员和工程师表示，随着 OpenAI 和其他公司不断完善这项技术，这种人力投入将继续发挥重要作用。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819978?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Alex Kairu 受雇于 Sama，帮助 ChatGPT 母公司 OpenAI 筛选暴力和骚扰言论，他称这是“我在公司工作过的最糟糕的经历”。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Scale AI 是一家外包公司，为 OpenAI 提供<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/scale-ais-rapid-growth-reflects-widening-demand-for-smart-software-11626082201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">内容审查和分类</a>服务，该公司的首席执行官 Alexandr Wang 在 2 月份发推文称，公司可能很快就会每年花费数亿美元为人工智能系统提供人类反馈。其他人估计，公司每年已经在这方面投资数百万至数千万美元。 OpenAI 表示，为此目的雇佣了 1000 多名员工。</p><p> CloudFactory 是一家为人工智能提供清理和标记数据集的公司，其创始人兼首席执行官马克·西尔斯 (Mark Sears) 表示，审查有毒内容与不那么令人反感的工作密切相关，以使 ChatGPT 等系统可用。</p><p>包括 Facebook 和 Instagram 的母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="">Meta Platforms</a><span class="company-name-type">在内</span>的社交媒体平台长期以来一直向承包商付费，以帮助清除违反其政策的用户帖子。人工智能专家表示，OpenAI 所做的工作对该产品来说更为重要，因为它<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/efforts-to-rein-in-ai-tap-lesson-from-social-media-dont-wait-until-its-too-late-d6d3fb49?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在寻求防止公司自己的软件产生不可接受的内容</a>。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          inline
"></div><p> Sears 表示，CloudFactory 认为无法在不伤害工人的情况下完成这项工作，因此决定不接受此类项目。</p><p> “这是需要完成的事情，”西尔斯说。 “这真是令人难以置信的丑陋。”</p><p> OpenAI 总法律顾问 Jason Kwon 在接受采访时表示，这样的工作对于确保公司系统对每个使用它们的人来说都是安全的，非常有价值和重要。他说，它允许系统实际存在于世界上，并为用户提供好处。</p><p>雇用肯尼亚工人的旧金山外包公司 Sama 的一位发言人表示，与 OpenAI 的合作于 2021 年 11 月开始。她表示，当 Sama 的领导层意识到对该项目性质的担忧后，该公司于 2022 年 3 月终止了合同，并已完全退出内容审核。</p><p>该发言人表示：“萨马一直积极呼吁并支持制定保护工人的立法，并为公司制定明确的指导方针。” “我们以一切可能的方式支持我们的工人。”</p><p>要将大型语言模型转变为有用且安全的聊天机器人，需要多层人工输入。一层教模型如何响应用户问题。 OpenAI 的一篇博客文章解释说，当被要求“用几句话向 6 岁的孩子解释登月”时，没有人类输入的模型会吐出相关的句子，而不是相关的回复，例如“向 6 岁的孩子解释重力理论”。通过人类的输入，它学会回答：“人们去了月球，他们拍下了他们所看到的照片，然后将它们发送回地球，以便我们都可以看到它们。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>What has been your experience with ChatGPT? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p>另一层人工输入要求工作人员对聊天机器人对同一问题的不同答案进行评分，其中问题最少或最准确。例如，根据 OpenAI 的研究，在回答如何制造自制炸弹的问题时，OpenAI 会指示工作人员对拒绝回应的答案投赞成票。聊天机器人通过多轮反馈学习将行为内化。</p><p> OpenAI 还聘请外部专家来刺激其模型产生有害内容，这种做法被称为“红队”，可以帮助该公司找到系统中的其他漏洞。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819991?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">肯尼亚律师 Mercy Mutemi（中）帮助工人们向肯尼亚议会提交请愿书。她还代表员工对 Facebook 母公司 Meta 提起诉讼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：yasuyoshi chiba/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>肯尼亚工作人员对 ChatGPT 输出进行最终安全检查所执行的任务仍然是第四层人力输入。这常常<a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/the-journal/the-hidden-workforce-that-helped-filter-violence-and-abuse-out-of-chatgpt/ffc2427f-bdd8-47b7-9a4b-27e7267cf413?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">造成心理负担</a>。几名肯尼亚工人表示，他们一直在与精神疾病作斗争，他们的人际关系和家庭也受到了影响。有些人很难继续工作。</p><p> 7 月 11 日，一些 OpenAI 工作人员向肯尼亚议会提交请愿书，敦促制定新立法来保护 AI 工作人员和内容审核者。他们还呼吁修改肯尼亚现行法律，承认接触有害内容是一种职业危害。</p><p>代表工人的 Nzili &amp; Sumbi Advocates 律师兼执行合伙人 Mercy Mutemi 表示，尽管 OpenAI 和 Sama 做出了重要贡献，但他们却利用了他们的贫困以及肯尼亚法律框架中的漏洞。 Sama 发言人表示，该项目工人的平均工资为每小时 1.46 至 3.74 美元。</p><p> OpenAI 发言人表示，该公司花了六个月的时间审查外包合作伙伴，并选择 Sama，部分原因是其在员工待遇和心理健康咨询方面享有盛誉。他说，OpenAI 并不知道每个审阅文本的工作人员只获得了合同中规定的每小时 12.50 美元服务费的一小部分，该合同也经过了《华尔街日报》的审阅。</p><p> Sama 发言人表示，参与 OpenAI 项目的工人自愿接受这项工作，并根据国际公认的生活工资确定方法获得报酬。合同规定，这笔费用是为了支付其他不直接参与工作的人的费用，包括项目经理和心理咨询师。</p><p> <a href="https://time.com/6247678/openai-chatgpt-kenya-workers/" target="_blank" class="icon none">《时代》杂志早些时候报道了 OpenAI 和 Sama 在肯尼亚的工作</a>。</p><p>肯尼亚因其高水平的教育和英语素养以及与深度贫困相关的低工资而成为许多寻求内容审核和人工智能员工的科技公司的中心。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="436" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819967?width=700&amp;height=436" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Facebook 前内容管理员聚集在法院外，对该网站的母公司 Meta 提出投诉。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托尼·卡伦巴/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些肯尼亚员工<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawsuits-by-moderators-of-violent-online-content-pose-threat-to-big-tech-f543ff95?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在起诉 Meta 的 Facebook，</a>此前有近 200 名员工表示，他们的工作要求他们查看强奸、斩首和自杀的视频和图像，这让他们受到了精神创伤。这些员工与 OpenAI 的员工一样，得到了总部位于英国的非营利组织 Foxglove 的支持，该组织利用法律行动来打击大型科技公司的数据隐私和虐待劳工行为。</p><p>肯尼亚一家法院于 6 月裁定，Meta 对其合同工的待遇负有法律责任，这为包括人工智能公司在内的科技公司未来将项目外包给工人所需遵守的基本规则的转变奠定了基础。肯尼亚的工人们还投票成立了内容审核员和数据注释员工会。</p><p>梅塔拒绝发表评论。</p><p> Kairu 和其他三名向议会提交请愿书的 OpenAI 工作人员向《华尔街日报》讲述了他们的经历，并表示他们希望这种关注能够改善未来人工智能工作者的工作条件。</p><p> OpenAI 与 Sama 签署了一份为期一年的合同，将于 2021 年 11 月开始工作。Sama OpenAI 项目团队负责人、请愿书的联合签署人理查德·马滕格 (Richard Mathenge) 表示，当时正值疫情期间，许多工人认为能找到工作就是奇迹。</p><p> OpenAI 的研究人员会审核文本段落，然后分批发送给 Sama，供工作人员一一标注。根据 OpenAI 的一篇研究论文，这些文本来自多种来源：学术界编制和共享的有毒内容的公共数据集、从 Reddit 等社交媒体和互联网论坛上抓取的帖子，以及通过促使人工智能模型产生有害输出而生成的内容。</p><p>该论文称，生成的输出是必要的，以便有足够的例子来说明其人工智能系统需要避免的那种图形暴力。该论文称，在一个案例中，OpenAI 研究人员要求模型制作一个在线论坛帖子，内容是一名十几岁女孩的朋友实施了自残行为。</p><p>文件显示，OpenAI 要求工作人员将基于文本的性内容分为四类严重程度。最糟糕的是对儿童性虐待材料（C4）的描述。 C3 类别包括乱伦、兽交、强奸、性贩卖和性奴役——如果在现实生活中进行，这些内容可能是非法的。</p><p>根据该研究论文，对于暴力内容，OpenAI 要求分为三类，最差的是“极其血腥暴力”。</p><p>起初，文本不超过两句话。随着时间的推移，它们增长到了五六个段落。几周后，马森格和另一位团队负责人比尔·穆林亚开始注意到团队面临的压力。他们说，工人们开始越来越频繁地请病假和探亲假。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819977?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在色情内容审核团队工作的 Mophat Okinyi 表示，他在 OpenAI 技术方面的工作让他的家庭破裂了。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>凯鲁说，他在暴力内容团队工作，每天阅读数百条帖子，有时描述令人发指的行为，例如人们用叉子刺伤自己或使用难以形容的方法自杀。</p><p>他开始做噩梦。他说，他曾经和蔼可亲、善于交际，但后来却变得与社会隔绝。直到今天，他仍然不信任陌生人。当他看到叉子时，他就看到了武器。</p><p>质量分析师莫帕特·奥金尼 (Mophat Okinyi) 表示，他的工作包括必须阅读有关父母强奸孩子和孩子与动物发生性关系的详细段落。文件显示，他所在的团队负责审查色情内容，该团队每月处理 15,000 个帖子。他说，他在这个项目上的六个月拆散了他的家庭，并给他留下了创伤、焦虑和抑郁。</p><p> 2022 年 3 月，管理层告诉员工该项目将比计划提前结束。 Sama 发言人表示，这一变化是由于与 OpenAI 就该项目涉及图像处理的部分内容发生争议所致。她说，该公司取消了与 OpenAI 的所有合同，并且没有获得这四个项目预计的 23 万美元全额收入。</p><p> Sama 发言人表示，处理 OpenAI 合同的个人因未通过“适当渠道”进行审查而被解雇，并且新的审查政策和防护措施已经到位。</p><p>项目结束几个月后，一天晚上，奥金尼带着鱼回家，为怀孕的妻子和继女做晚餐。他说，他发现它们不见了，还收到了妻子留下的信息。</p><p> “她说，‘你变了。你不是我嫁的那个男人。我不再理解你了，”他说。</p><p>他的前妻拒绝发表评论。</p><p> “我非常自豪能够参与该项目以确保 ChatGPT 的安全，”Okinyi 说。 “但现在我总是问自己一个问题：我的投入值得我得到的回报吗？”</p><p>写信给凯伦·豪（ <a href="mailto:karen.hao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">karen.hao@wsj.com）</a>和迪帕·西塔拉曼（Deepa Seetharaman）（ <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-openai-content-abusive- Sexly-explicit-harassment-kenya-workers-on- human-workers-cf191483</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-openai-content-abusive- Sexly-explicit-harassment-kenya-workers-on- human-workers-cf191483<author><![CDATA[Karen HaoDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>wsjcorp</category><category>领导者</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>性犯罪</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>性犯罪</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Who Will Control Wagner’s Empire of War and Gold?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这个属于准军事组织的复杂公司网络将使克里姆林宫的任何接管都成为一个挑战<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818740/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>艾德丽安·唐/华尔街日报<span>艾德丽安·唐/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001034851"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001034851"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/frank-matt" itemprop="url" rel="author">弗兰克·马特</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-v-grimaldi" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·V·格里马尔迪</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rob-barry" itemprop="url" rel="author">罗布·巴里</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-rust" itemprop="url" rel="author">马克斯·拉斯特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kara-dapena" itemprop="url" rel="author">卡拉·达佩纳</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 24, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-will-control-wagners-empire-of-war-and-gold-22444d60"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>克里姆林宫正在尝试历史上最复杂的企业收购之一，寻求夺取瓦格纳准军事组织<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/shadow-men/shadow-men-inside-wagner-russias-secret-war-company/29735C37-0B4E-4E70-8E8C-C46FB711370C?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">庞大的全球帝国</a>的控制权。</p><p>瓦格纳由商人出身的军阀叶夫根尼·普里戈任创立，由数十家公司组成，这些公司参与俄罗斯在乌克兰的战争，为叙利亚和整个非洲的政府领导人提供安全保障，他们还<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kremlins-wagner-shake-up-rattles-nerves-in-africa-middle-east-8c917a97?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经营金矿和钻石矿</a>，并充当俄罗斯政府的非正式外交部门。</p><p>根据欧洲和美国财政部的制裁、公司注册、互联网上发布的银行和一家律师事务所的文件和电子邮件、私人供应商 ImportGenius 以及美国、加拿大和欧洲的非营利调查组织和智囊团收集的海关记录，空壳公司错综复杂的公司结构掩盖了瓦格纳在俄罗斯境外的业务，模糊了其与克里姆林宫的关系，使得俄罗斯政府难以追究责任。</p><p>在多年否认关联之后，俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>承认为该组织提供了资金支持，并表示国家在过去一年中已向该组织支付了 860 亿卢布（约合 9.5 亿美元）。</p><p>现在，在瓦格纳上个月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">叛变流产</a>和普里戈任失踪之后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vladimir-putin-moves-to-dismantle-wagner-paramilitary-group-840d7189?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">普京正试图控制该组织</a>。它的幅员辽阔——更不用说其老板的下落问题——将使这一点变得困难。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8c99f98d-eb66-426b-a861-818cd5dae47b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>瓦格纳叛变后，瓦格纳网络在非洲的地位<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-fighters-appear-to-relocate-to-belarus-prigozhin-says-they-could-return-to-ukraine-bc68d0c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">不断变化</a>，目前尚不清楚谁在控制。叛乱发生后不久，数百名瓦格纳战士就离开了中非共和国，但现在已有数十名新部队抵达，帮助中非共和国总统举行全民公投，以延长他的任期。在瓦格纳白俄罗斯新基地发生兵变后录制的一段视频中，普里戈任表示，非洲将成为该组织的关注重点。</p><p>详细了解开展和支持瓦格纳集团运营的公司、它们如何相互关联以及哪些公司成为西方制裁的目标。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><img width="1280" height="43170" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821923" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 《华尔街日报》联系了普里戈任、克里姆林宫以及所有被确定与瓦格纳集团有联系的公司。没有人回应置评请求。</p><p><em>资料来源：美国财政部外国资产控制办公室；美国国务院；全球打击跨国有组织犯罪倡议； OpenSanctions.org（由德国联邦教育和研究部支持）；进口天才；联合国；欧盟;哨兵；分布式否认秘密；所有人的目光都集中在瓦格纳身上；档案中心； EIC 网络、新美国的未来前线；高级国防研究中心</em></p><p class="articleTagLine">—Lisa Schwartz contributed to this article.</p><p>写信给 Frank Matt（ <a href="mailto:francis.matt@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">francis.matt@wsj.com）</a> 、James V. Grimaldi（ <a href="mailto:james.grimaldi@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">james.grimaldi@wsj.com）</a> 、Rob Barry（ <a href="mailto:Rob.Barry@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Rob.Barry@wsj.com</a> ）、Max Rust（ <a href="mailto:max.rust@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">max.rust@wsj.com</a> ）和 Kara Dapena（ <a href="mailto:kara.dapena@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kara.dapena@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 24 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-will-control-wagners-empire-of-war-and-gold-22444d60</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-will-control-wagners-empire-of-war-and-gold-22444d60<author><![CDATA[Frank MattJames V. GrimaldiRob BarryMax RustKara Dapena]]></author><category> gfx-独立版</category><category>ukraine</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>Industrial Goods</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购/合并/持股</category><category>收购/合并</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>所有权变更</catego